That completely depends on the database at hand.  You&#039;ll have to monitor the fragmentation in order to determine the need for rebuilds or reorganization steps.  &lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Give you an example:  I have one database that is around 100GB.  In this database I update stats for about 20 tables every 4 hours and then nightly rebuilds.  These types of work tables require very active maintenance to keep them running well but the lock scenario of course is a consideration.  Some other indexes on large archived tables and or static tables get rebuild monthly just because there is no need.

There is some excellent information in this article struggling to get out.  However, sentences like these make me question the skill of the author:&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&quot;So in that it is critical that in the position of supporting any database that you have queries running on that it is performing to the best it can be.&quot;  &lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&quot;Fragmentation is easy to handle as long as you handle it.&quot;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
